    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-01-12T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-01-12T17:00:00-05:00" n="118"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d118">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">839.918/3: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé des Affaires in the Dominican Republic</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Brewer</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-01-12T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 12, 1920—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1. After consultation with Navy Department and Mr. Russell it is considered that
                    since censorship has been practically abolished by the order of December 22 from
                    Military Governor to Brigade Commander, an executive order should be issued
                    abolishing censorship but continuing in force all regulations in regard to
                    publication of articles outlined in said order to Brigade Commander and holding
                    civilly and criminally responsible violators of its provisions. Consult with
                    Military Governor at once on this subject.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
